  "primaryContentSections" : [
    {
      "content" : [
        {
          "anchor" : "Overview",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Overview",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Binary representations of whole numbers",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Conversion between number systems",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Uses for hex",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Bases",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Bases",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "In everyday life, we mostly use the Base-10 number system, also known as decimal, or denary.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "However, computers store data using bits, and cannot use decimal directly. Instead, they use Base-2, or binary, which",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "uses 0 and 1 as the only digits.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Another number system often used when working with computers is Base-16, or hexadecimal. It has 16 distinct digits, 0-9",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "and A-F. A-F represents the numbers 10-15.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "These are not the only numerical bases, you can theoretically have any number system with any number. The examples",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "below are not tested, and are here for enrichment.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Base-8, octal, is used to represent Unix File Permissions (and was used in the early days of computing).",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Base-60, sexagesimal, is used in measuring time, angles (in degrees), bearings, and geographic coordinates.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Applications-of-Number-Systems",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Applications of Number Systems",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "RGB-Colour-Codes",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "RGB Colour Codes",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "RBG is an abbreviation of red, green, and blue, which are the primary colours of light and can be combined with varying",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "intensities to create other colours.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "The intensity of each colour component is stored as a number, and each value is stored in a single byte, corresponding",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "to 000000002 to 111111112, 0016 to FF16, and 0 to 255 in binary, hexadecimal, and decimal respectively.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "When all 3 colour intensities are 0, the result is black. If all intensities are at their maximum, the result is white.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "RGB colour codes are displayed in the form of #RRGGBB, where RR, GG and BB are 2-digit hexadecimal numbers that represent",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "each component of the colour. These codes are used to represent colours in websites, typically written in HTML and CCS.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Network-Addresses",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "Network Addresses",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "For computers to communicate\/exchange data over a network, they must be able to locate each other so that transmitted",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "data cn be directed to the correct destination.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "This is done by giving each computer a unique name in the form of a sequence of bytes called a network address.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "The Internet is an example of a computer network, each computer on the Internet has an IP address, serving as its network",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "address on the internet.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "IP (internet protocol) is a standard system of rules used by computers on the Internet to communicate with each other.",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "There are 2 versions of IP used today, IP version 4 and IP version 6.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "IPv4",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                },
                {
                  "items" : [
                    {
                      "content" : [
                        {
                          "inlineContent" : [
                            {
                              "text" : "An internet protocol that is made up of 4 bytes (32 bits). Usually shown as a sequence of 4 denary",
                              "type" : "text"
                            },
                            {
                              "text" : " ",
                              "type" : "text"
                            },
                            {
                              "text" : "numbers, one for each byte of the address, separated by dots.",
                              "type" : "text"
                            }
                          ],
                          "type" : "paragraph"
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "content" : [
                        {
                          "inlineContent" : [
                            {
                              "text" : "Since the value of a byte can only vary from 0 to 255, none of the 4 denary numbers can fall out of this range.",
                              "type" : "text"
                            }
                          ],
                          "type" : "paragraph"
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "content" : [
                        {
                          "inlineContent" : [
                            {
                              "text" : "The maximum number of IPv4 addresses is 232, or 4.3 billion. With the rapid growth of the Internet in the 80s and",
                              "type" : "text"
                            },
                            {
                              "text" : " ",
                              "type" : "text"
                            },
                            {
                              "text" : "90s, the number of IPv4 addresses is insufficient.",
                              "type" : "text"
                            }
                          ],
                          "type" : "paragraph"
                        }
                      ]
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "unorderedList"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "IPv6",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                },
                {
                  "items" : [
                    {
                      "content" : [
                        {
                          "inlineContent" : [
                            {
                              "text" : "An internet protocol that is made up of 16 bytes (128 bits). Usually shown as a sequence of 8 hexadecimal numbers, each",
                              "type" : "text"
                            },
                            {
                              "text" : " ",
                              "type" : "text"
                            },
                            {
                              "text" : "number being 16 bits. Each group uses 4 hexadecimal digits.",
                              "type" : "text"
                            }
                          ],
                          "type" : "paragraph"
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "content" : [
                        {
                          "inlineContent" : [
                            {
                              "text" : "Hexadecimal is used for representation as using decimal would take up a maximum of 3 × 16 = 48 digits, which is inconvenient.",
                              "type" : "text"
                            }
                          ],
                          "type" : "paragraph"
                        }
                      ]
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "unorderedList"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "MAC-Address",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "MAC Address",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Media Access Control (MAC) address – A sequence of bytes (usually permanent in nature) that is used to identify a particular",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "network interface controller.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "It is a permanent way to locate or identify a specific computer or device, as the IP address of a computer may change each time",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "it connects to the internet.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "It is made up of 6 bytes (48 bits), and is shown as a sequence of 6 hexadecimal numbers, one for each byte of the address. They",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "are separated either by colons or hyphens.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "The format for a MAC address is NN-NN-NN-DD-DD-DD, where NN-NN-NN is the manufacturer’s identity number; and DD-DD-DD is the",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "device’s serial number.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "ASCII-and-Unicode",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "ASCII and Unicode",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "ASCII is a standard that defines how numbers are used to represent common characters that can be typed using a keyboard,",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "such as uppercase and lowercase letters. Only 128 distinct characters can be represented as ASCII codes are defined to be",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "exactly 7 bits long.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "The first 32 ASCII codes (0-31) represent non-printing characters that are not written symbols or the space character. They",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "are used to control devices or represent special input such as the backspace and escape keys on a keyboard.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "The last ASCII code, 127, is used to represent the special input of typing the delete key.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Hexadecimal digits are often used to express these codes as only 2 digits are needed, which is more compact than 3 decimal digits",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "or 7 binary digits.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "An expanded standard called Unicode is used to represent other characters, such as Mandarin characters. It uses numbers to",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "represent characters like ASCII, but are not as restrictive in the number of bits they must be defined as. The number of bits",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "used to represent each character can range from 8-32 bits, allowing over a million unique characters from many different written",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "languages all over the world, making it preferable over ASCII.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "kind" : "content"
    }
